  var $ = window.jQuery
  var Waypoint = window.Waypoint

  /* http://imakewebthings.com/waypoints/shortcuts/sticky-elements */
  function Sticky(options) {
    this.options = $.extend({}, Waypoint.defaults, Sticky.defaults, options)
    this.element = this.options.element
    this.$element = $(this.element)
    this.createWrapper()
    this.createWaypoint()
  }

  /* Private */
  Sticky.prototype.createWaypoint = function() {
    var originalHandler = this.options.handler

    this.waypoint = new Waypoint($.extend({}, this.options, {
      element: this.wrapper,
      handler: $.proxy(function(direction) {
        var shouldBeStuck = this.options.direction.indexOf(direction) > -1
        var wrapperHeight = shouldBeStuck ? this.$element.outerHeight(true) : ''

        this.$wrapper.height(wrapperHeight)
        this.$element.toggleClass(this.options.stuckClass, shouldBeStuck)

        if (originalHandler) {
          originalHandler.call(this, direction)
        }
      }, this)
    }))
  }

  /* Private */
  Sticky.prototype.createWrapper = function() {
    if (this.options.wrapper) {
      this.$element.wrap(this.options.wrapper)
    }
    this.$wrapper = this.$element.parent()
    this.wrapper = this.$wrapper[0]
  }

  /* Public */
  Sticky.prototype.destroy = function() {
    if (this.$element.parent()[0] === this.wrapper) {
      this.waypoint.destroy()
      this.$element.removeClass(this.options.stuckClass)
      if (this.options.wrapper) {
        this.$element.unwrap()
      }
    }
  }

  Sticky.defaults = {
    wrapper: '<div class="sticky-wrapper" />',
    stuckClass: 'stuck',
    direction: 'down right'
  }

properties.text:
This 'Text' component is located inside of the 'Content Collection (footer)' element you can see in the 'elements tree' on the left hand side.

The 'Content Collection (footer)' and 'Content Collection (top)' are defined on the 'Home Page' and displayed across other pages so that you don't need to define your header and footer over and over again.

Let's start with creating a few components from the "General" section in the "Create element" popup that shows up after a click on the plus icon button (you can find it on the left hand side just above the "elements tree" when having one of its elements selected, you can also find it when clicking on a "Headline" or "Text" or any other "component" added here in the "editor" area). If you're still uncertain what we are talking about or you haven't seen our Quickstart screencast video, you can watch it here.

So here we go.

We have put together this demo prototype to make your first days with PrototypeBrewery more productive. We aim to get this demo to cover every single available component eventually. Today, we'd like to show you a few "components" to start with to give you an idea what can be done here. As a new user who hasn't gone through PrototypeBrewery Docs page you might not know that, for example, you can create a link that will trigger a popup when clicked on. Things like that.

We hope you'll find it useful. If you don't... give us a shout via our website and let us know what we can improve on!

If you look to the top left section of this admin panel you notice 'Legal copy' page. Let's say we need to include some repetitive content on every page. Piece of cake. Use the 'Content References' component and look up your element using its name you assigned it with (in our case it's: Legal copy element).

So the below legal copy is being pulled from another page we created: Legal copy. You can go there and check it out. We also prevented that page from being automatically listed in the site's top bar navigation in the top right corner.
This is a sample alert text.
This one has got the appearance option set to 'Warning'. We also set the 'Radius or rounded style' option to 'radius' setting.
You can add Font-Awesome powered icons and set them to different sizes and make them do other stuff: e.g. rotate to use it with 'Submit' buttons in loading state.

The below 'Carousel' component is just a standard carousel with a few predefined options set in the right hand side element inspector. We might add more variations in here later on, we might not. Doesn't really matter, does it? Go ahead and experiment with replacing the 'Image' elements from the inside of the 'Carousel' component with some HTML to build your own custom carousels or add some slide captions.

So here is the thing about this whole grid row and grid column gibberish: we have predefined four most demanded layouts - one, three, two and four columns that your content goes into to make things a bit more civilised. Those columns now can be heavily customised.Â 

  • you can hide one of your columns when a user visits the page on his mobile phone or tablet or desktop
  • you can decide that you want those columns to take less/more space when viewed on phone/tablet/desktop
  • you can simply stack those columns on top of each other - choose whether you want it to happen for phones only or for tablets and phones
  • you can swap their order - let's say you have two columns and they appear stacked when viewed on a phone but you want the 2nd column appear to the left of the 1st column (in a reverted order)
